@flexiarg equity/contribution-pathways
@title Recipients Without Voice Remain Recipients
@keywords co-ownership, contribution, governance, community, collective-choice, NPT, Ostrom, agency, becoming
@audience programme designers, community coordinators, futon coordination layer
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [equity/ARGUMENT equity/shared-maintenance equity/visible-impact]

! conclusion: Engagement sustains when participants become co-producers with recognised scope to shape the programme — not just consumers of a centrally defined offer. Without contribution pathways, the agent's becoming is capped: they can develop local competence but not reshape the system that shapes them.
  + context: A programme needs trainers to sustain engagement beyond the initial training wave. In NPT terms this is Cognitive Participation (2.4 Activation): how procedures and actions that can sustain delivery are collectively defined. In Ostrom's terms this is the collective-choice problem: can affected participants modify, extend, and help govern the programme, or only consume it? In the whole-board-play analogy, Patterns 1-3 gave the agent the rules, the conditions to play, and a way for local learning to propagate backward. This pattern asks whether the agent can modify the rules themselves.
  + IF:
    Trainers have developed local competence through iterative delivery (Pattern 2) and their adaptations are flowing into the shared commons (Pattern 3). The system is learning from its own variation. But the trainers' relationship to the system is still one of consumption: they receive the programme, they adapt it locally, they upstream improvements — but they do not govern how the programme evolves. Their learning improves the materials but does not give them a voice in the programme's direction, priorities, or structure.
  + HOWEVER:
    There are no explicit pathways for contribution beyond delivery and materials upstream. No peer cohorts, no shared adaptation reviews, no mentoring structure. The Community of Practice exists on paper but most trainers are unaware of it. Peer channels have been created but go unused. The ORCA coordinator role — which should serve as the backbone of community infrastructure — is undertrained and under-supported. The agent's becoming is capped: they can develop as a deliverer but not as a co-governor. This is like an AlphaZero that can play and learn within the game but cannot modify the game's parameters, training regime, or architecture. It remains a creature of its original design, however skilled it becomes within those constraints. In human systems, this cap on becoming is felt as: "At some point I potentially leave with that knowledge and it doesn't get used as much as it could have."
  + THEN:
    The programme builds community infrastructure from the start: peer exchange channels that are actually stewarded (not just created), mentoring structures, and a coordinator role that is properly resourced and trained. Visible routes to share, mentor, or adapt turn private motivation into repeated participation. Crucially, these are not just communication channels — they are governance instruments. Through them, the trainers who do the hardest lifting gain recognised scope to shape what the programme becomes. The shift from recipient to co-producer is not just a change in role but a change in the kind of agent the person is: from a local adapter operating within fixed constraints to a co-governor whose experience reshapes the constraints themselves.
  + BECAUSE:
    Sen: Capability expands when participants can move from receipt to co-ownership and contribution. But the deepest capability expansion is not skill development — it is the transition from being shaped by a system to shaping it. This is the becoming that equity requires: not just the freedom to act within given conditions, but the freedom to revise the conditions under which action takes place.

    Whole-board play: In the AlphaZero analogy, this is the transition from playing within a fixed architecture to modifying the architecture itself — changing the learning rate, the network structure, the reward signal. In human systems, this transition is what distinguishes a community of practice from a distribution list. A distribution list delivers content. A community of practice co-evolves the content, the delivery, and the governance of both. The trainers who sustain engagement are not just good players — they are people whose experience should reshape how the game is set up for future players.

    Ostrom: This is the collective-choice arrangement: positions and recognised scope determine whether participants can organise and contribute. Community infrastructure that is created but not stewarded is indistinguishable from no infrastructure. Without contribution pathways, motivation remains individual and exits with the person. This is where the equity loop either closes or breaks: contribution that creates recognised stake, stake that gives governance rights, governance that improves the conditions for future contribution. If this joint breaks, the system is extractive — it benefits from the trainer's labour without giving them a voice.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Resource and train the coordinator role before expecting community to emerge
    - Steward peer channels actively — facilitated, not just created
    - Define explicit contribution pathways: adaptation review, mentoring, programme governance
    - Design governance so that sustained contribution creates recognised standing
    - Test: does a motivated trainer have a visible route into co-ownership within their first year?
    - This requires governed infrastructure (high coordination) and should be resolved after conditions 1-3
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Every participant who sustains engagement beyond initial training has at least one visible route to contribute to programme development, governance, or community support. Sustained contribution creates recognised standing in the programme's governance structure.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Capped becoming: agent develops local competence but cannot reshape the system
    - Goodwill dependency: practice survives only as long as the individual persists
    - Invisible community: CoP exists formally but trainers are unaware of it
    - Dead channels: peer exchange channels created but unstewarded and unused
    - Undertrained coordinators: ORCA role exists but "reactive rather than helpful"
    - Knowledge exit: "at some point I potentially leave with that knowledge and it doesn't get used"
    - Extraction: system benefits from trainer labour without granting governance voice
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T1 ("That ownership felt really important to me")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T1 ("I wouldn't have delivered that training if I hadn't had this framework")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T3 ("At some point I potentially leave with that knowledge")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T1 ("I don't think I was aware of the Community of Practice")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T2B ("in theory, there's a teams channel, but I've never seen anyone use it")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T3 ("the ORCAs really didn't get any training")
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Cognitive Participation (2.4 Activation) via the UKRN T3 analysis.
    Mapped to the equity loop at contribution→stake→governance: contribution without recognised scope is extraction.
    Deepened via whole-board play: the transition from playing within fixed constraints to modifying the constraints is the transition from recipient to co-governor.
    Ostrom: positions and collective-choice arrangements determine whether participants can organise and contribute.
    Coordination requirement: High (infrastructure).
